White schrieb dazu (mail): "That Bible was at the Mannheim court before 1803, then the Staatsbibliothek in Munich, then the English collector Robert Curzon [Baron Zouche] from 1832, [bis 1920 in Familienbesitz, dann durch Mary Cecil Frankland, Baroness Zouche, versteigert bei Sotheby, Nov. 1920, Lot 70, an Joseph Sabin; Quelle: McCune collection website], and finally the dealer Gabriel Wells [New York], who sold the individual leaves with the essay in 1921"; Wikipedia: "The leaves were sold in a portfolio case with an essay written by A. Edward Newton, and were referred to as 'Noble Fragments'". Im 18. Jh. Besitz von Maria Elisabeth Augusta von Sulzbach; 1832 als Dubl. d. Münchner Hofbibl. versteigert (Powitz 1990, Zensus Nr. 47)
